{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}} {{Infobox tennis biography |name = Albert Burke |fullname = |image = Albert Burke 1922.jpg |caption= |country={{flagu|Ireland}} |birth_date = 1901 |birth_place = |death_date = November 1958 (aged 57) <ref>https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1958/11/23/110083044.pdf</ref> |death_place = |turnedpro = |retired = |tennishofyear = |tennishofid = |highestsinglesranking = |AustralianOpenresult = |FrenchOpenresult = |Wimbledonresult = |USOpenresult = |Othertournaments = |Olympicsresult = |doublesrecord = |doublestitles = |highestdoublesranking = |currentdoublesranking = |AustralianOpenDoublesresult = |FrenchOpenDoublesresult = |WimbledonDoublesresult = |USOpenDoublesresult = |OthertournamentsDoubles = |Promajors = yes |USProresult = QF ([[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1927–1945#1931|1931]], [[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1927–1945#1932|1932]]) |WembleyProresult = QF ([[Wembley Professional Championships Draws#1935|1935]]) |FrenchProresult = 2nd ([[French Pro Championship draws#1930|1930]]) |OlympicsDoublesresult = |Mixed = |mixedrecord = |mixedtitles = |AustralianOpenMixedresult = |FrenchOpenMixedresult = |WimbledonMixedresult = |USOpenMixedresult = |OthertournamentsMixedDoubles = |OlympicMixedDoublesresult = }}
'''Albert Burke''' (1901–1958) was an [[Irish people|Irish]] professional [[tennis]] player based in [[France]]. Albert Burke was the son of Thomas Burke. Thomas Burke was a professional [[tennis]] player when professional [[tennis]] began in the late 19th century and Albert Burke's brother Edmund Burke was also a professional [[tennis]] player.<ref>http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k292971p/f6</ref> Albert Burke won the Bristol Cup in France - the top professional tournament in the world in the 1920s - in 1924 and 1925, beating [[Roman Najuch]] in both finals.<ref>http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k273619h/f6</ref> He was also losing finalist in the Bristol Cup in 1926, 1929 and 1931, losing all three finals to [[Karel Koželuh]].<ref>http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k296481k/f9</ref> Burke finished second in the 1930 [[French Pro Championship]] round robin, while [[Karel Koželuh]] was the winner.<ref>http://www.tennis.co.nf/frenchpro.htm</ref> At the [[US Pro Tennis Championships]] Burke was a quarter finalist in 1931 (losing to [[Howard Kinsey]]) and 1932 (losing to [[Bill Tilden]]).<ref>http://www.tennis.co.nf/uspro.htm</ref> At the [[Wembley Championships]] Burke lost in the quarter finals in 1935 against [[Ellsworth Vines]].<ref>http://www.tennis.co.nf/britishpro.htm</ref>
