{{Infobox person | name = Jean Stein | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = Jean Babette Stein | birth_date = {{birth date|1934|2|9}} | birth_place = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]], U.S. | death_date = {{death date and age|2017|04|30|1934|2|9}} | death_place = [[New York City]], New York, U.S. | death_cause = Suicide | known_for = | occupation = Author, editor | spouse = {{ubl|[[William vanden Heuvel]]|{{marriage|[[Torsten Wiesel]]|1995|2007|end=divorced}}}} | children = {{ubl|[[Katrina vanden Heuvel]]|Wendy vanden Heuvel}} | parents = {{ubl|[[Jules C. Stein]]|Doris Jones}} }}
'''Jean Babette Stein ''' (February 9, 1934 – April 30, 2017) was an American author and editor.
==Early life== Stein was born to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family in Chicago.<ref name="nytobit"/> Her father was [[Jules C. Stein]] (1896–1981), founder of the [[MCA Inc.|Music Corporation of America]] (MCA) and the Jules Stein Eye Institute at [[University of California, Los Angeles]]. Her mother, Doris J. Stein (1902–1984), established the Doris Jones Stein Foundation. Jean Stein's sister, [[Susan Shiva]], died of breast cancer (1983), as did Doris Stein.<ref name=TheLastMogul>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8zV1aziv9CYC&pg=PA531&lpg=#v=onepage&q=jones&f=false |title=The Last Mogul: Lew Wasserman, MCA, and the Hidden History of Hollywood |first=Dennis |last=McDougal |authorlink=Dennis McDougal |publisher=[[Da Capo Press]] |year=2001 |page=27 |isbn=978-0306810503}}</ref>
Stein was educated at the Katharine Branson School in [[Ross, California]], then at [[Brillantmont International School]] in [[Lausanne]], [[Switzerland]], after which she graduated from [[Hewitt School|Miss Hewitt's Classes]] in New York City. Thereafter, she spent two years at [[Wellesley College]] and then attended classes at the [[University of Paris]] (formerly known as the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]]). While in Paris she interviewed [[William Faulkner]], with whom she had an affair,<ref>Natalie Robins. Alien Ink: The FBI's War on Freedom of Expression (New Brunswick: Rutgers U Press, 1992), pp. 424-5.</ref> and, according to the historian Joel Williamson, offered the interview to ''[[The Paris Review]]'' in exchange for being made an editor there.<ref>Joel Williamson. William Faulkner and Southern History (New York: Oxford University Press, 1995), p. 304</ref>
==Career== Stein returned to New York and worked in 1955 as assistant to director [[Elia Kazan]] on the original production of [[Tennessee Williams|Tennessee Williams's]] [[Pulitzer Prize]] winning play ''[[Cat on a Hot Tin Roof]]''.<ref>{{IBDB name | id=jean-stein-104252}}</ref>
Stein was the author of three books and a pioneer of the narrative form of oral history. Her final work was a cultural and political history of Los Angeles, ''West of Eden'', published by [[Random House]] in February 2016. In 1970, Stein authored, with [[George Plimpton]] as editor, a biography of [[Robert F. Kennedy]], titled ''American Journey: The Times of Robert Kennedy''.
With Plimpton, Stein co-wrote the best-selling book ''Edie: American Girl'', based on the life of socialite/actress and [[Andy Warhol]] muse [[Edie Sedgwick]], in 1982.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=6XCIqw48uSwC&pg=PP13&dq=Jean+Stein+george+Editor+Edie&sig=ACfU3U0LkKRN3-Th98DUOAjo6WjNNtKEZQ ''Edie: American Girl'' review]</ref> [[Norman Mailer]] wrote of ''Edie'': "This is the book of the Sixties that we have been waiting for."{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}
Stein also worked as a magazine editor. In the late 1950s she was an editor, with Plimpton, at ''The Paris Review''. From 1990 to 2004, she was editor of the literary/visual arts magazine ''Grand Street'' with art editor [[Walter Hopps]]. The magazine actively sought out international authors, visual artists, composers and scientists to bring to its readership.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}
==Legacy== In 2017, Stein partnered with [[PEN American Center|PEN America]] to launch the PEN/Jean Stein Book Award and the PEN/Jean Stein Grant for Oral History to honor groundbreaking literature. The annual $75,000 PEN/Jean Stein Book Award, which is awarded to a book of fiction, memoir, essay, or nonfiction, “focuses global attention on remarkable books that propel experimentation, wit, strength, and the expression of wisdom.”<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/books/la-et-jc-pen-75000-book-prize-20160720-snap-story.html|title=PEN America launches $75,000 book prize, one of the country's biggest|date=2016-07-20|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-08-03|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> [[Hisham Matar]], a Libyan-American writer, won the 2017 inaugural award for his memoir, ''The Return.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pen.org/2017-penjean-stein-book-award|title=2017 PEN/JEAN STEIN BOOK AWARD - PEN America|date=2017-03-27|work=PEN America|access-date=2017-08-03|language=en-US}}</ref> The $10,000 PEN/Jean Stein Grant for Oral History is awarded to support the completion of a “literary work of nonfiction that uses oral history to illuminate an event, individual, place, or movement.”<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pen.org/literary-award/penjean-stein-grant-for-literary-oral-history-10000/|title=PEN/Jean Stein Grant for Literary Oral History ($10,000) - PEN America|work=PEN America|access-date=2017-08-03|language=en-US}}</ref>
==Personal life== Stein's first marriage in 1958 was to [[William vanden Heuvel]], a lawyer who served in the U.S. Justice Department under [[Robert F. Kennedy]], and who later also became a diplomat and author. Since 1984, he has been the chairman of the [[Roosevelt Institute]]. Their first daughter, [[Katrina vanden Heuvel]], was born in 1959; she is now the editor and publisher of ''The Nation'' magazine. The couple's second daughter, Wendy vanden Heuvel, was born in 1961, and she is an actress and producer in New York. She is also on the board of the ''52nd Street Project'', which matches inner-city youth with professional theater artists to create original dramatic works.
From 1995 to 2007, Stein was married to [[Torsten Wiesel]], a co-recipient with [[David H. Hubel]] of the 1981 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
Suffering from depression, Stein apparently committed suicide by jumping from her Manhattan apartment on April 30, 2017. She was 83.<ref name="nytobit">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/02/books/jean-stein-dies-chronicled-wealth-fame-and-influence.html?_r=0 |title=Jean Stein, Who Chronicled Wealth, Fame and Influence, Dies at 83 |first=Richard |last=Sandomir |authorlink=Richard Sandomir |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |page=A25 |date=May 2, 2017}}</ref>
